        <body>
           <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl" resp="#NW" source="MAC1945">
            <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name nymRef="laidagnas?">ᚂᚐᚔᚇᚐᚅᚅ</name> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">ᚋᚐᚊᚔ</w> <name nymRef="maqqas_corbo?">ᚋᚐᚉᚑᚏᚁᚑ</name></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl" resp="#NW" source="MAC1945">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name nymRef="laidagnas?">LAIDANN</name> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">MAQI</w> <name nymRef="maqqas_corbo?">MACORBO</name></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
           <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app n="1"><note>Macalister (1945, 136) noted that <q>the readings of all three of these stones must remain tentative until the cave can be dismantled</q>.</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>           
            <div type="translation">
                <p>of Laidánn son of Mac-Corb?</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>As noted by Ziegler (1994, 192), the name <persName xml:lang="sga">Laidáinn</persName> (gen. sg.) occurs in the genealogies (CGH S. 670) and may contain the word <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/29367">laíd</ref></foreign> 'poem' with the individualising suffix -án (often -ANN in incriptions). The father's name, MACORBO, probably consists of a first element MAQI/MAC 'son of' and a second either <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="dil.ie/12433">corb</ref></foreign> 'chariot' (compare Mac-Corb in the genealogies CGH S. 681) or <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target=" dil.ie/33941">orb(b)a</ref></foreign> 'heritage, inheritance' (compare Mac-Orbba in the genealogies CGH S.683) (Ziegler 1994, 200). This name is also found in a number of other inscriptions, e.g. I-WAT-011, I-WAT-022 and possibly also I-KIK-002.</p>
            </div>
